    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix incorrect AMF counter handling in ngap_gNB_remove_amf_desc()\n\n### Summary\nThe `ngap_gNB_remove_amf_desc()` function properly removes all AMF descriptors from the red-black tree and frees associated memory, but fails to reset the instance counters (`ngap_amf_nb`, `ngap_amf_pending_nb`, `ngap_amf_associated_nb`) to zero. This causes inconsistent state where the counters still reflect the presence of AMF associations that have actually been removed.\n\nThis can lead to unexpected behavior in other parts of the NGAP stack that rely on these counters to make decisions about AMF availability and registration status.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair3/NGAP/ngap_gNB_management_procedures.c`: Added counter resets after removing all AMF descriptors to ensure consistent state.\n\n### Reproduction\nUnder certain network conditions where AMF associations are repeatedly established and torn down, the gNB may fail to properly register with new AMF instances due to stale counter values. This manifests as failed NG setup procedures and connection establishment failures for UEs.\n\nThe issue becomes apparent when:\n1. AMF associations are established (counters incremented)\n2. `ngap_gNB_remove_amf_desc()` is called to clean up all associations\n3. New AMF associations are attempted\n4. The NGAP stack incorrectly believes AMF associations still exist due to non-zero counters\n"
}